Here's how to collect assembly-loading diagnostics for your `AssemblyLoadContext` issue:

### 1. Enable the Fusion-style trace via environment variables

```bash
export DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts=""
export COREHOST_TRACE=1
export COREHOST_TRACEFILE=host_trace.log
dotnet run
```

`COREHOST_TRACE` logs every probing path the host checks during startup.

### 2. Enable EventPipe assembly-load tracing (runtime-level)

```bash
dotnet-trace collect \
  --providers Microsoft-Windows-DotNETRuntime:0x4:4 \
  -- dotnet run
```

`0x4` is the `AssemblyLoader` keyword. This captures every `AssemblyLoadContext.Load` / `Resolving` event, including which context requested what and why it failed.

### 3. Inspect the `LoaderExceptions` array

The most direct clue is usually in the exception itself:

```csharp
try
{
    var types = assembly.GetTypes();
}
catch (ReflectionTypeLoadException ex)
{
    foreach (var loaderEx in ex.LoaderExceptions)
        Console.WriteLine(loaderEx);   // often FileNotFoundException with the exact missing assembly + version
}
```

### 4. Subscribe to the runtime resolve events (code-level)

```csharp
AssemblyLoadContext.Default.Resolving += (ctx, name) =>
{
    Console.WriteLine($"[Default ALC] failed to resolve: {name.FullName}");
    return null;
};

myCustomAlc.Resolving += (ctx, name) =>
{
    Console.WriteLine($"[Plugin ALC] failed to resolve: {name.FullName}");
    return null;
};
```

### Typical root causes

| Symptom in trace | Likely fix |
|---|---|
| Missing transitive dependency | Publish plugin with `--self-contained` or ensure deps are beside the plugin DLL |
| Version mismatch on shared type | Make sure host and plugin reference the **same version** of the shared contract assembly |
| Type loaded in two ALCs | Move shared interfaces/types into an assembly loaded only in the **Default** context |

Start with **step 3** — the `LoaderExceptions` array almost always names the exact missing or mismatched assembly.
